To implement performance monitoring, use `beforeAgentCallback` to store the start time and `afterAgentCallback` to calculate duration. Here's a complete implementation:
typescript
import { SingleAgentCallback } from '@google/adk';

export const START_TIME_KEY = 'start_time';

export const agentStartCallback: SingleAgentCallback = (context) => {
  if (!context?.state) return undefined;
  context.state.set(START_TIME_KEY, Date.now());
  return undefined;
};

export const agentEndCallback: SingleAgentCallback = (context) => {
  if (!context?.state) return undefined;
  const now = Date.now();
  const startTime = context.state.get<number>(START_TIME_KEY) || now;
  console.log(
    `Performance Metrics for Agent "${context.agentName}": ` +
    `Total Elapsed Time: ${(now - startTime) / 1000} seconds.`
  );
  return undefined;
};

Attach these callbacks to agents to log execution times during their lifecycle.

Callback hooks enable conditional step skipping through validation in `beforeModelCallback`. For instance:
typescript
import { SingleAgentCallback } from '@google/adk';

export const validationCallback: SingleAgentCallback = (context) => {
  if (!context?.state) return undefined;
  const projectData = context.state.get('project_data');
  if (!projectData?.isValid) {
    console.log('Skipping LLM evaluation - invalid project data');
    context.state.set('skip_evaluation', true);
    return undefined;
  }
  return undefined;
};

Attach this to an LLM agent's `beforeModelCallback` to bypass model execution when prerequisites aren't met, reducing costs and latency.
